</p>
<p>Only one of these side - in this case the <code>Genus</code> - is the <em>owning</em> side. So far,
that hasn't meant anything: we can easily <em>read</em> data from either direction. BUT!
The owning side has one special power: it is the <em>only</em> side that you're allowed
to change.</p>
<p>What I mean is, if you have a <code>User</code> object and you add or remove genuses from its
<code>studiedGenuses</code> property and save... Doctrine will do <em>nothing</em>. Those changes
are completely ignored.</p>
<p>And it's not a bug! Doctrine is built this way on purpose. The data about which
Genuses are linked to which Users is stored in <em>two</em> places. So Doctrine needs
to choose <em>one</em> of them as the official source when it saves. It uses the <em>owning</em>
side.</p>
<p>For a <code>ManyToMany</code> relationship, we chose the owning side when we set the <code>mappedBy</code>
and <code>inversedBy</code> options. The owning side is also the only side that's allowed to
have the <code>@ORM\JoinTable</code> annotation.</p>
<p>This is a <em>long</em> way of saying that if we want to update this relationship, we <em>must</em>
add and remove users from the <code>$genusScientists</code> property on <code>Genus</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="9ce4a0eb27">
    <div class="meta">
        <div class="actions">
            <span class="fa fa-clipboard js-activate-clipboard" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Copy Code" data-placement="top"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="info">
                        <span class="js-expand-all" data-range="1-197" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Show All Lines" data-placement="top">
                <i class="fa fa-expand js-icon-load-more"></i>
                <i class="fa fa-spinner fa-spin js-icon-loading"></i>
            </span>
            
            197 lines <span class="meta-divider"></span> <span title="src/AppBundle/Entity/Genus.php">src/AppBundle/Entity/Genus.php</span>
        </div>
    </div>
